'''Adam Michael Shankman''' (born November 27, 1964) is an American [[film director]], [[Film producer|producer]], dancer, actor and [[choreography|choreographer]].  He has been a judge on the television program ''[[So You Think You Can Dance]]'' since Season 3. He began his professional career in [[musical theatre]], and was a dancer in music videos for [[Paula Abdul]] and [[Janet Jackson]]. Shankman also choreographed one of the Spice Girls' tours. He has directed several feature-length films, including ''[[A Walk to Remember]]'', ''[[Bringing Down the House (film)|Bringing Down the House]]'', and ''[[Hairspray (2007 film)|Hairspray]]''.

==Early life==
Shankman was born in [[Los Angeles, California]] to an [[upper middle class]] family.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.filmreference.com/film/54/Adam-Shankman.html| title = Adam Shankman Biography| publisher = [http://www.filmreference.com/ Film Reference]| accessdate = 2007-07-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://buzzsugar.com/391531| title = Buzz Interview: Hairspray's Nikki Blonsky and Adam Shankman | publisher = [[Sugar Publishing]] [http://buzzsugar.com/ BuzzSugar]| accessdate = 2007-07-20}}</ref> He had a "traditional [[Jew]]ish upbringing" in [[Brentwood, Los Angeles, California|Brentwood]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/33036/format/html/displaystory.html
| title = <U+2018>Hairspray<U+2019> director, starlet are kindred (Jewish) spirits | author = Michael Fox| publisher = [[j.]]| accessdate = 2007-07-20}}
</ref> He attended [[The Juilliard School]], but dropped out to dance in musical theater.<ref name=white>White, Dave (March 4, 2003), "Master of the house". ''Advocate'' (884):56-57</ref> 

==Career==
{{quote box|align=left|width=210px|quote=Juilliard didn't really acknowledge theater dancing as dancing. To them, it was some sort of clownlike bastardization of the arts.|source=''Advocate'' magazine,<ref name=white/> 2003}}
Shankman was a dancer in Janet Jackson's <U+201C>Escapade<U+201D> video,<ref name=white/> as well as in a MC Skat Kat video with Paula Abdul.  Shankman broke into professional choreography in a 1989 music video for rapper MC Shan with director Julien Temple.  When the hired choreographer fell through, Shankman lied and said that he had done choregraphy for Janet Jackson and Paula Abdul.  He was hired on the spot without his story being verified.<ref name=white/>  Shankman began choreographing movies that included actors such as [[Marlon Brando]], [[Sarah Jessica Parker]], [[Antonio Banderas]], and the cast of ''[[Boogie Nights]]''.<ref name=white/>  He is [[Brendan Fraser]]'s exclusive choreographer.<ref name=white/>

In 1996, Shankman was represented by the newly formed Sauce Entertainment, a production company for music videos and commercial production.<ref name=white/><ref>Atwood, Brett (June 29, 1996), "MTV L.A. offices: Movin' on out; C&D for Pennywise vid". ''Billboard''. '''108''' (26):91</ref>  In 1998, he was a choreographer for the program "Win Ben Stein's Money".<ref>Stein, Benjamin J. (May 1998), "A golden age for thugs". ''American Spectator''. '''31''' (5):58</ref>

Shankman's first directing gig was for a short film called ''Cosmo's Tale'', which appeared at the [[Sundance Film Festival]].<ref name=white/>  He then helped his sister, [[Jennifer Gibgot]], on a script, which led to a meeting with the studio producing ''[[The Wedding Planner]]''. He was hired for the job ten minutes into the meeting.<ref name=white/>  In May 2003,  Shankman filed a $5 million lawsuit against Jennifer Lopez, asserting that he came up with the idea for her adaptation of the opera ''[[Carmen (opera)|Carmen]]''.<ref>Schwartz, Missy; Brown, S. Tia; Tucker, Ken (May 30, 2003), "Monitor". ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''. (712):22</ref>

Prior to directing ''Hairspray'', Shankman was known in Hollywood primarily as a fixer of [[Low culture|lowbrow]] films<U+2014>a director who could take charge of lackluster productions that were expected to flop and turn them into box-office hits.  His trademarks in his films often features a singing/dancing sequence and a character getting sent to do [[community service]].  "I've done so many things I'm not super-proud of," he admitted in an interview with the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''.  Having finally received a plum directing role in ''Hairspray'', he added, "Now that I'm finally really proud of something, if [critics] say this one isn't good either, it will be kind of...taxing."<ref>''Ibid.''</ref>  In August 2008, ''Box office Mojo'' reported that ''Hairspray'' had become the fourth-largest grossing American movie musical within the previous 30 years.<ref>[http://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=musical.htm Box Office Mojo]</ref>

Shankman, in affiliation with ABC, worked on a TV pilot called ''Harmony'' about a musical town.<ref>Rice, Lynette (November 2, 2007), "TV Execs: 'Please Don't Stop the Music!'". ''Entertainment Weekly''. (982):16</ref>  "A new series about the female mayor of a small town has jumped from the back burner to the front, thanks to [Governor] [[Sarah Palin]]. The proposed show, tentatively titled "[[Cadillac Ranch]]," comes with a big-name director attached - Adam Shankman..."<ref>[http://www.nypost.com/seven/10102008/tv/palin__the_tv_series_132885.htm NYPost: PALIN, THE TV SERIES]</ref>

He has just been announced to be directing the film adaptation of the musical [["Rock of Ages"]] from [[New Line Cinema]]. The film will begin production in Summer of 2010.<ref>http://www.playbill.com/news/article/133970-Shankman_Will_Direct_Rock_of_Ages_on_Screen</ref>

On October 20 2009 it was announced he will be one of the two producers of the 82nd Academy Awards on March 7 2010 .[http://www.deadline.com/hollywood/exclusive-adam-shankman-bill-mechanic-will-produce-oscars/#more-17726][http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/10/20/producers-named-for-oscars-telecast/]

===''So You Think You Can Dance''===
{{quote box|align=right|width=220px|quote=The great thing about this show is that we've really explored a totally new thing which is lyrical hip hop and [Tabitha and Napoleon] nail it. This show has shown that hip hop is just a completely legitimate beautiful genre in and of its own and you can tell such beautiful and heart breaking stories.|source=Shankman, June 25, 2008 episode of ''SYTYCD''<ref>"The Top 16 Perform". ''So You Think You Can Dance''. [[25 June]] [[2008]]. No. 10, season 4.</ref>}}
Shankman has been a judge and choreographer on the FOX reality show ''[[So You Think You Can Dance]]'' since Season 3. He used the term "[[Hip hop dance#Lyrical hip-hop|lyrical hip-hop]]" to describe the dance style associated with the choreography duo of [[Napoleon and Tabitha D'umo|Tabitha and Napoleon D'umo]]. The term is popularly credited to him as reported in the May/June 2009 issue of ''Dance Spirit'' magazine.<ref>Levinson, Lauren. (May/June 2009), [http://www.dancespirit.com/articles/2131 "Lyrical Hip Hop'"]. ''Dance Spirit''. '''13''' (5):48-50 (accessed [[2009-04-25]])</ref>

On September 16, 2009, it was announced that Adam will be a permanent judge on <i>[[So You Think You Can Dance]]</i>.<ref>{{cite news | author=Adam Bryant | title=Adam Shankman Made Permanent Judge on So You Think You Can Dance | url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Shankman-Judge-Dance-1009766.aspx | work=TVGuide.com | date=16 September 2009 | accessdate=2009-09-16}}</ref>

